===Articles===

* '''Brett Frischmann, "An [[Economic Theory of Infrastructure and Commons Management]], (89 Minnesota Law Review 4, April 2005)'''

URL = http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=588424; 

Brett Frischmann, a professor at Loyola University Chicago School of Law has published an essay that is “a rigorous, clear-headed explanation of the economic and social benefits of commons-based infrastructures":

“The basic problem with relying on markets to allocate access to common assets, Frischmann explains, is that the market mechanism exhibits a bias for outputs that generate observable and appropriable returns at the expense of outputs that generate positive externalities" 

#(Commentary from On the Commons blog, at http://onthecommons.org/node/613; 
#a bio on the author at http://www.luc.edu/law/faculty/frischmann.shtml)



* Berlant, Lauren. 2016. ‘The Commons: Infrastructures for Troubling Times*’. Environment and Planning D: Society and Space 34 (3): 393–419. doi:10.1177/0263775816645989.

